comment.body:
We can (and do) mark them as required, but in this step, there are not error messages specific to fields, as we're dealing with an unbound form.

Previously, if there were some required fields, the user was immediately presented specific error messages on the bound form. It would also be fine for me to not show a message at all and just let the user work with the form, but the imprecise message "Some fields" with a warning level feels like bad UX (especially since this is the first time the user can see this form, so in contrast to a user not filling out a required input, there is no user error in this case).

Another option would be to "downgrade" this message from `warning` to `info` and reword it so that it sounds less like a user error, e.g.:

> We need some additional information to sign you up for this shift

UPSTREAM: f2fs: fix UAF in f2fs_available_free_memory

if2fs_fill_super
-> f2fs_build_segment_manager
   -> create_discard_cmd_control
      -> f2fs_start_discard_thread

It invokes kthread_run to create a thread and run issue_discard_thread.

However, if f2fs_build_node_manager fails, the control flow goes to
free_nm and calls f2fs_destroy_node_manager. This function will free
sbi->nm_info. However, if issue_discard_thread accesses sbi->nm_info
after the deallocation, but before the f2fs_stop_discard_thread, it will
cause UAF(Use-after-free).

-> f2fs_destroy_segment_manager
   -> destroy_discard_cmd_control
      -> f2fs_stop_discard_thread

Fix this by stopping discard thread before f2fs_destroy_node_manager.

Note that, the commit d6d2b491a82e1 introduces the call of
f2fs_available_free_memory into issue_discard_thread.

Cc: stable@vger.kernel.org

ANDROID: android-verity: Prevent double-freeing metadata

If extract_metadata() fails, it will free metadata in its own error
path, so it is safe to simply return the provided error value without
worrying about resource handling/releasing.

Moreover, if we simply return in extract_metadata()'s error path, we
can assume the thread of execution will only make it down into the
free_metadata: tag area sometime after extract_metadata()'s success,
in which case metadata will need to be freed without question.

Fixed `--graph`/`--no-graph` and `--patch` OOM.

Currently using `--graph` and `--patch` together may run out of memory for large repos.

However, if `revs->graph` is initialized at least once, the arguments parser function consider it somewhere in invoked code (where?) in the parsing loop.

No idea why the arguments parser does not merely sets flags first, and then, and only after that, does all required initialization.
I don't care the hell it is implemented.
This stupid patch just works.

issue.title: [Feature Request] Align file & folder structure with metadata and pattern
issue.body:
# Align file & folder structure with metadata and pattern

**What problem or limitation are you encountering?**  
After I adjust metadata, files and folders are not aligned with these changes. For example, if I change an author "Bryson, Bill" to "Bill Bryson" to align with the rest of the books, the file is still in a folder "Bryson, Bill" because it was imported that way.

**What solution or improvement do you propose?**  
A button that detects all file paths of tracked books that do not align with the default pattern and that moves them. 

**Have you found any workarounds or alternatives?**  
No, except for manual labour.

**Additional details**  
N/A

Filling this in like a form makes it sound a bit impersonal, but I like to have a filesystem that aligns with the metadata. Not 5 folders with slightly different spellings of the same author. I can fix this by manually moving and rescanning (I think), but fixing this from BookLore itself would be fantastic.

comment.body: Personally I believe you have suggested a needed feature. Possibly adding a settings option under metadata or patterns like ‚Äúupdate after save‚Äù or ‚Äúorganize after save‚Äù which would perform a move using the current default pattern (if set).
